Cox Proportional Hazards Model

Author

Lianghui Yi

Introduction

  • Why Use the Cox Proportional Hazards Model?
    • It evaluates the relationship between survival time and covariates without assuming a specific baseline hazard function.
    • Allows adjustment for confounding variables such as demographic, biomarkers and clinical characteristics.
  • Primary Objective:
    • To compare PFS between two treatment groups while adjusting for potential confounding factors.
  • Secondary Objectives:
    • Visualize adjusted survival probabilities to clarify treatment effects.
    • Verify model assumptions using Cox-Snell residuals to ensure validity.

# Load Library
library(survival)

# Prepare the data
# CNSR: Event indicator (0 = event occurred, 1 = censored)
data$CNSR <- as.numeric(data$CNSR)
# AVAL: Time to event
data$AVAL <- as.numeric(data$AVAL)
# TRT01P: Treatment Method
data$TRT01P <- as.factor(data$TRT01P)

Feature Selection

We used Kaplan-Meier curves to identify potential predictors of PFS. The following variables were selected based on the log-rank test.

  • Demographic variables
  • Biomarkers
  • Clinical characteristics

Features List

Key Feature - Treatment Group

Bio-Markers - LDH (Lactate Dehydrogenase) - ALB (Albumin) - HGB (Hemoglobin)

Demographic Factors - SEX

Clinical Characteristics - TOTAE (Count of adverse events) - ECOG (Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group performance status)

Code 
selected_columns <- c("TRT01P", "ECOG", "HGB", "TOTAE", "SEX")
# selected_columns <- c("TOTAE", "ETHNIC")
selected_columns

# convert the selected columns to a formula
formula <- as.formula(
  paste("Surv(AVAL, 1-CNSR) ~", paste(selected_columns, collapse = "+"))
)
  1. 'TRT01P'
  2. 'ECOG'
  3. 'HGB'

Fitting the Cox Proportional Hazards Model

Code 
# Fit the Cox model
cox_model <- coxph(
  formula,
  data = data
)

Model Summary Interpretation

Coefficients

  • A positive coefficient suggests that the hazard increases with the covariate (e.g., higher TOTAE is associated with higher risk).
  • A negative coefficient suggests that the hazard decreases with the covariate (e.g., one treatment plan may reduces risk).

Hazard Ratio

  • Represents the hazard ratio (HR), which quantifies the effect of a covariate on the hazard rate.
    • HR > 1: Covariate increases the hazard (worse survival).
    • HR < 1: Covariate decreases the hazard (better survival).
  • For example:
    • TOTAE: IF HR = 1.1, A 1-unit increase in adverse events decrease the hazard by 10%.
    • Treatment B: IF HR = 0.84. Treatment B reduces the hazard by 16% (1 - 0.84) compared to the reference group (Treatment A).

Concordance Index (C-Index)

The concordance statistic (C-index) measures the model’s predictive accuracy: Values range from 0.5 (no predictive ability) to 1.0 (perfect prediction).

The concordance index is 0.56, which indicates that the model is slightly better than random chance.

Visualize the proportional hazards assumption check

This computes the Schoenfeld residuals for the Cox model to test whether the proportional hazards assumption holds for each covariate.

The test evaluates if the effect of each covariate on the hazard ratio changes over time.

A significant change indicates a violation of the proportional hazards assumption.

Code 
plot(cox.zph(cox_model))

Key Points to Look For

  1. Flat Line at 0: Suggests the proportional hazards assumption holds.
  2. Upward/Downward Trends: Indicates potential time-varying effects of the covariate, violating the proportional hazards assumption.
  3. Random Fluctuations: Small random fluctuations around 0 are normal and not concerning.

Follow-Up Actions if Assumption is Violated

If a covariate shows a significant violation: 1. Time-Dependent Covariates: Consider modeling the covariate as time-dependent (e.g., using interaction terms or tt() in coxph). 2. Stratification: Use stratified Cox models (strata()) to handle covariates that violate the proportional hazards assumption. 3. Alternative Models: Consider other survival models, such as the accelerated failure time (AFT) model.

Doing Adjusted Survival Curves

Adjusted survival curves are used in Cox proportional hazards models to visualize the survival probabilities while accounting for the effects of covariates. They present survival estimates that are adjusted for the average or specific values of covariates, allowing a more accurate comparison between groups (e.g., treatment groups).

Code 
# Fix Covarites
# Plot the adjusted survival curves for specific predictors:
# generated new data with the features set as the mean of the data other than TRT01P
newdata <- data.frame(
  TRT01P = c("TREAT A", "TREAT B"),
  TOTAE = mean(data$TOTAE, na.rm = TRUE),
  LDH = mean(data$LDH),
  ECOG = mean(data$ECOG),
  ALB = mean(data$ALB),
  HGB = mean(data$HGB),
  # get the most common value of SEX
  SEX = names(sort(table(data$SEX), decreasing = TRUE))[1]
)

Checking the fit of the model by doing Residual analysis

Cox-Snell residuals are used to assess the goodness-of-fit of a Cox proportional hazards model. The residuals provide insight into how well the model fits the data by comparing the observed survival to the expected survival under the fitted model.

Code 
data$resid_mart <- residuals(cox_model, type = "martingale")
data$resid_coxsnell <- -(data$resid_mart - (1 - data$CNSR))
fit_coxsnell <- coxph(
  formula = Surv(resid_coxsnell, (1 - CNSR)) ~ 1,
  data = data,
  ties = c("efron", "breslow", "exact")[1]
)

df_base_haz <- basehaz(fit_coxsnell, centered = FALSE)
ggplot(data = df_base_haz, mapping = aes(x = time, y = hazard)) +
    geom_point() +
    scale_x_continuous(limit = c(0,3)) +
    scale_y_continuous(limit = c(0,3)) +
    labs(x = "Cox-Snell residuals as pseudo observed times",
         y = "Estimated cumulative hazard at pseudo observed times") +
    theme_bw() + theme(legend.key = element_blank())

Conclusion

  • Cox regression revealed differences in PFS between treatment groups.
  • We also incorprated adjusted survival analysis clarified covariate effects.
  • Using Cox-Snell Residual diagnostics support model validity.
  • In real scenarios, when checking the proportional hazards assumption, we may need to consider time-dependent covariates or alternative models. If that is the case, we can use stratified Cox models or other survival models such as AFT models.
